A data structure is a specific way of organizing and storing data in a
 computer so that it can be accessed and used efficiently.

A linear data structure is a way of organizing data elements in a sequential 
manner, where each element is connected to a single predecessor and successor
 (except for the first and last elements). This arrangement allows for
  straightforward, single-pass traversal of all elements. 


Non-linear data structures organize data hierarchically or in networks
 rather than sequentially, allowing for efficient, multi-level modeling of 
 complex relationships. Unlike linear structures (arrays, lists), they store
  elements in non-sequential memory, often using pointers to represent relationships,
   with key examples being trees and graphs
